On the ultimate goal and where the story closes:
This is the question that makes everything else make sense. Let me propose it and you tell me if it's right:
The story closes when the prophecy is completed — not broken, not prevented, not escaped. Completed. But completed in a way the Silent Court, the order, and everyone who manipulated it never intended.
The prophecy was always about the bloodline producing something the universe needed. The Silent Court thought they knew what that was. They were wrong. What the bloodline actually produced — across three siblings, across all the loss and transformation and becoming — is the end of the system that was managing prophecy in the first place.
Not a new ruler. Not a new empire. The dismantling of the architecture that made empires feel inevitable.
The story ends not with Conq on a throne. It ends with him standing somewhere — maybe with the child, maybe with the fatherless daughter, maybe alone — in a universe that no longer has a Silent Court, no longer has an order whispering in the ears of rulers, no longer has a bond governing his bloodline.
